SIMPLE: subject
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Subject
<hw>Sub*ject"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>suget</ets>, OF. <ets>souzget</ets>, <ets>sougit</ets> (in which
the first part is L. <ets>subtus</ets> below, fr. <ets>sub</ets> under),
<ets>subgiet</ets>, <ets>subject</ets>, F. <ets>sujet</ets>, from L.
<ets>subjectus</ets> lying under, subjected, p. p. of
<ets>subjicere</ets>, <ets>subicere</ets>, to throw, lay, place, or
bring under; <ets>sub</ets> under + <ets>jacere</ets> to throw. See
<er>Jet</er> a shooting forth.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Placed or
situated under; lying below, or in a lower situation.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Placed under the power of another; specifically
<fld>(International Law)</fld>, owing allegiance to a particular
sovereign or state; <as>as, Jamaica is <ex>subject</ex> to Great
Britain</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Esau was never <qex>subject</qex> to Jacob.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Exposed; liable; prone; disposed; <as>as, a country
<ex>subject</ex> to extreme heat; men <ex>subject</ex> to
temptation.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All human things are <qex>subject</qex> to decay.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Obedient; submissive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Put them in mind to be <qex>subject</qex> to principalities.</q>
<rj><qau>Titus iii. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Liable; subordinate; inferior; obnoxious;
exposed. See <er>Liable</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Subject</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Subject
<hw>Sub*ject"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From L. <ets>subjectus</ets>,
through an old form of F. <ets>sujet</ets>. See <er>Subject</er>,
<pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which is placed under the
authority, dominion, control, or influence of something else.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically: One who is under the authority of a
ruler and is governed by his laws; one who owes allegiance to a
sovereign or a sovereign state; <as>as, a <ex>subject</ex> of Queen
Victoria; a British <ex>subject</ex>; a <ex>subject</ex> of the United
States.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Was never <qex>subject</qex> longed to be a king,⟦br⟧
As I do long and wish to be a <qex>subject</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>subject</qex> must obey his prince, because God commands
it, human laws require it.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In international law, the term <xex>subject</xex> is
convertible with <xex>citizen</xex>.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is subjected, or submitted to, any
physical operation or process; specifically <fld>(Anat.)</fld>, a dead
body used for the purpose of dissection.</def> <-- also, an animal or
person which is studied in a scientific experiment. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That which is brought under thought or examination;
that which is taken up for discussion, or concerning which anything is
said or done.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧This <xex>subject</xex> for heroic
song.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Make choice of a <qex>subject</qex>, beautiful and noble, which .
. . shall afford an ample field of matter wherein to expatiate.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The unhappy <qex>subject</qex> of these quarrels.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>The person who is treated of; the hero of a piece;
the chief character.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Writers of particular lives . . . are apt to be prejudiced in
favor of their <qex>subject</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>C.
Middleton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Logic & Gram.)</fld> <def>That of which anything is
affirmed or predicated; the theme of a proposition or discourse; that
which is spoken of; <as>as, the nominative case is the <ex>subject</ex>
of the verb</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>subject</qex> of a proposition is that concerning which
anything is affirmed or denied.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>That in which any quality, attribute, or relation,
whether spiritual or material, inheres, or to which any of these
appertain; substance; substratum.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That which manifests its qualities -- in other words, that in
which the appearing causes inhere, that to which they belong -- is
called their <qex>subject</qex> or substance, or substratum.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <def>Hence, that substance or being which is conscious of
its own operations; the mind; the thinking agent or principal; the ego.
Cf. <er>Object</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The philosophers of mind have, in a manner, usurped and
appropriated this expression to themselves. Accordingly, in their hands,
the phrases <qex>conscious</qex> or <qex>thinking subject</qex>, and
<qex>subject</qex>, mean precisely the same thing.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Hamilton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>The principal theme, or leading
thought or phrase, on which a composition or a movement is
based.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The earliest known form of <qex>subject</qex> is the
ecclesiastical <qex>cantus firmus</qex>, or plain song.</q>
<rj><qau>Rockstro.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>10.</sn> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <def>The incident, scene, figure,
group, etc., which it is the aim of the artist to represent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Subject</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Subject
<hw>Sub*ject"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Subjected</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Subjecting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To bring
under control, power, or dominion; to make subject; to subordinate; to
subdue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Firmness of mind that <qex>subjects</qex> every gratification of
sense to the rule of right reason.</q> <rj><qau>C.
Middleton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In one short view <qex>subjected</qex> to our eye,⟦br⟧
Gods, emperors, heroes, sages, beauties, lie.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He is the most <qex>subjected</qex>, the most <?/nslaved, who is
so in his understanding.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To expose; to make obnoxious or liable; <as>as,
credulity <ex>subjects</ex> a person to impositions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To submit; to make accountable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God is not bound to <qex>subject</qex> his ways of operation to
the scrutiny of our thoughts.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To make subservient.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Subjected</qex> to his service angel wings.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To cause to undergo; <as>as, to <ex>subject</ex> a
substance to a white heat; to <ex>subject</ex> a person to a rigid
test</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1434 --></p>

<p><ent>Subjected</ent>⟦br⟧
